the linker flags as if it was a static library.

Keep InCallUI in memory (1/3)

up to 10 seconds when the device is busy, which prevents the user

attribute set to true and allows the activity from Dialer.apk,
which uses the com.android.incallui process to be loaded into the

issue.title: Trick for automatically serializing eagerly loaded associations?
issue.body: Just a minor issue that I'm struggling with at the moment. It appears that the default instance implementation of toJSON detects and automatically serializes any eagerly loaded associations on the model. However, the name that the associations are loaded under is the capitalized and pluralized name of the association. So if I have a 'Topic' model with a 'Category' association such that `Topic.belongsTo(Category)`, if I eagerly load the category with the topic, I get `topic.Category`. Obviously this is a trivial example but I'm wondering if there is some way to access a list of eagerly loaded associations from within the toJSON() instance method so that I can programmatically rename and serialize all of the eagerly loaded associations?

issue.title: Idea: Backward harvest with Mex 5
issue.body:
Hello Courseplay team,

This idea began while testing #832 "Mais harvesting with poetinger mex 5" and the provided fix. As this is a new question/idea/request I decided to open a new "Issue" instead of placing this in the other thread.

With Mex5 attached at tractor front and using Courseplay v256 works now perfect.

I did a little research and found at Mex5 manufacturer home page (Pöttinger, see also links at the end) that it is also/more common to attach a Mex5 at the back of a tractor and then driving backward at harvest. I tried this configuration in LS 15 together with Courseplay v256... 

Initial the transport tractor driven by Courseplay joins the harvester in the "wrong" direction (screenshot 1). So I stopped Courseplay at transport tractor. Then I drove the transport manually to the "right" direction.  After I start Coursplay again at transport tractor the transport follows my backward driving harvester (screenshot 2) very good/as expected ;-) ... 

So my question: Is there an easy way to implement something like a "default backward/forward driving" flag to indicate the normal driving direction for such a harvest combine? So the transport would be able to evaluate such a flag and already initially joins in the "right" driving direction... 

Or is this just a nut idea from my side as this is not a very common usage of CP in LS 15?

Screen1

Martin

Cary,

First try of the type information. It seems quite stable, been using it for a few days (provided the configuration is correct, I suppose, didn't test what happens when ghc-modi is not correctly configured).

I bound the type info call to the DocumentationProvider as well as to an action (alt - equals, like scala). I prefer the action, I think the documentation provider doesn't work so well. Also, there is a weird behaviour that getting the editor creates a stack trace of around 5 kilometers long, something that seems like a threading issue, but the function seems to work. I don't really know why the stack trace happens, all the more because it only happens when calling the type information through the documentation provider (same code path is used when the action is called, but no stack trace). Maybe you know more what could go wrong, it looks like something intellij-related.

So, consider this a "request for comment" more than a pull request ;-)

Kasper

issue.title: DataCustodian grants authorization code if no scope is provided
issue.body:
A DataCustodian has potentially many scopes for its services. However, a small subset, often one, is valid for a specific customer. Therefore, a scope provided by the DataCustodian to the ThirdParty must be offered to the authorization code request service so that the OAuth layer will allocate the correct scope.

The alternative is that the OAuth server will authorize all scopes available from the third party registration for the customer. For example, assume that the third party is supporting gas and electric customers. This fault will authorize gas and electric for a customer who only has electric service. 

It appears that the authorization service is more permissive and needs some mechanism to require this field in the authorization code request.

comment.body:
Can you clarify what you mean by "this scope is provided to the ThirdParty on the redirect from the Data Custodian to the Third Party"?  Which redirect are you referencing, because the scope is not provided until the ThirdParty receives the response to the oauth/token endpoint which is a 200 OK not a 302 Redirect.

The scope selection screen is presented to the Retail Customer by the Authorization Server after the retail customer is authenticated by the Resource Server.  This is done so the Authorization Server does not know the identity of the Retail Customer, merely that the Resource Server has authenticated the individual granting access.  The scope selection screen displays ALL scope strings defined that are available for the Third Party and the Retail Customer approves as many of the scope strings as they desire.  The scope portion of the access token JSON structure then contains all of the retail customer "approved" strings.  Therefore, how can we assure only one scope is returned in the actual access token response and it matches the one provided to the ThirdParty if the initial oauth/authorize request does not contain a "scope=" parameter?

issue.title: Operators and [Double] support for beCloseTo matching
issue.body:
In a nutshell:
```
expect(1.0) ~= 1.0001
expect(1.0) == (1.002, 0.005)
expect(1.0) == 0.9 ± 0.2
```
I've also added matching of Double arrays (identical delta for all elements):
```
expect([0.0, 1.0]) ~= [0.0001, 1.0001]                       // using the default delta of 0.0001
expect([0.0, 1.0]).to(beCloseTo([0.1, 1.1], within: 0.1))    // using the given delta of 0.1
```

comment.body:
Thanks for the pull request, @feinstruktur! :wave: :grin: 

RSpec dropped support for matcher operators like `==` when they migrated to the `expect(...).to(...)` syntax, primarily due to [runtime warnings from the Ruby interpreter](http://myronmars.to/n/dev-blog/2012/06/rspecs-new-expectation-syntax). Since we don't have that problem in Swift, I'm not opposed to matcher operators.

I'm largely ambivalent, though.

I don't think they provide enough value to justify the lines of code needed to define them--even if that's a very small amount. But I personally don't use them, so I really can't speak to how useful they are! :speak_no_evil: :banana: 

I would say that `~=` reminded me of the Ruby operator `=~`, so I think I'd find it confusing to use. But again, I don't normally use matcher operators, so take that with a grain of salt.

pull_request.title: Bundle Collision with SGM file
pull_request.body:
# Description:
We have an optimised & preprocessed file format called SGM that was written by Luomu but, for some reason, we don't ship SGM files in with the main distribution. Part of that reason was that it helped loading times a lot but not as much as it could have due to the collision mesh generation being excluded from it.

With the merging of #3099 giving us 3 very complex new space stations and very complex collision meshes I've tried to add support for serialising and deserialising the collision meshes into our SGM format.

## Distribution:
With this change it would make sense to build the `.SGM` files in-place, delete the `.DAE` from the build and only have them in Git and `pioneer-assets`. 
This way players don't have to worry about having the correct files or building `.SGM` versions.

# Loading times:
A quick comparison, please note that this is done on my laptop with a 512GiB SSD so there's little variation due to disk access, but possibly some due to thermal throttling/behaviour.

## SGM Load times:
I did 3 runs and the times were
* Loading took: 23865.460385 milliseconds
* Loading took: 23486.056590 milliseconds
* Loading took: 23832.089322 milliseconds
For an average of **~23727.87** milliseconds.

## Standard Load times:
Once again but with no SGM files.
* Loading took: 128687.466982 milliseconds
* Loading took: 126967.270705 milliseconds
* Loading took: 126556.816863 milliseconds
For an average of **~127403.85** milliseconds

## Result:
This means that using SGM files with the collision mesh data results in the game loading to the intro screen **~5.37** times faster.

# At the Command line:
**WARNING**: The SGM files this creates will be chosen in preference to the original data in future so you might miss updates to files. Best to delete all of these SGM files after experimenting with this **WARNING**

To recreate the SGM files you just need to build the ModelCompiler, this should be shipped with the binaries versions, or you can build it yourself. It's built alongside Pioneer.
Simply go to the Pioneer folder where ModelCompiler & Pioneer reside, open a prompt / terminal and enter something like: `modelcompiler -b inplace`
That will create an SGM file for every model in the game and place it next to it's `.model` file.

# Status:
Worth testing, as I've just fixed the bug I had caused and collision now works again. Loads fast and works!

I've chosen to **compress** all of the SGM files the modelcompilier produces as this results in a reduction from ~132MB down to just ~39.5MB which is a significant reduction. It does have a negative impact on the loading times, raising it from an average 20 seconds to 24 seconds. However I think this is more than worth it.

Andy

Volsung - ScaledHigh (from Scaled) - it has a crappy enchantment, so it needs the armor rating boost.

pull_request.title: New Whitelist / Blacklist Filter
pull_request.body:
This new filter will behave either as a blacklist or a whitelist. If the value being filtered exists in the list of known values, the filter will return the value if its a whitelist or `null` if its a blacklist. The opposite will happen if value is not in the list.

### Whitelist
```php
$whitelist = new \Zend\Filter\Whitelist(array(
    'list' => array('allowed-1', 'allowed-2')
));
echo $whitelist->filter('allowed-2');   // => 'allowed-2'
echo $whitelist->filter('not-allowed'); // => null
```

### Blacklist
```php
$blacklist = new \Zend\Filter\Whitelist(array(
    'type' => 'blacklist', // optional, default is 'whitelist'
    'list' => array('not-allowed-1', 'not-allowed-2')
));
echo $blacklist->filter('allowed');        // => 'allowed'
echo $blacklist->filter('not-allowed-2');  // => null
```

### Notes  

1. Maybe calling the filter class `Whitelist` might be counter-intuitive if the desired behavior is that of a blacklist. But I couldn't think of a better way to name the filter, so I'm open to suggestions:
    * Something like "AllowedList" would just be a synonym of "whitelist". 
    * "List" would just be too vague.
    * Separate filter classes seemed overkill.
2. I decided to allow only one type of configuration in the constructor (by array of options) just to keep it simple. If you'd like to allow for a more dynamic constructor (like a few other filters do) let me know.
3. Not sure what commit edbc12b is doing in this PR. Looks like its in `master` but not in `develop`.

See #6960 for more info.

issue.title: Use photo's stored elsewhere on the system
issue.body:
Hi,

Not really a bug report, but a feature request as you will.

I stumbled upon your beautiful and easy-to-use Photo-Management-System and together with @GustavePate his lycheesync plugin I thought to have finally found _the_ gallery software I was looking for. But Gustave's plugin seems to be copying my local photo folder to Lychee instead if "indexing" it and using the local photo folder as source to serve the original photo.

Is it possible with Lychee to use an existing photo repository (like /data/photos/*) and "Index" that folder structure into Lychee? Not modifying the original repo in the process, storing generated thumbnails etc. inside the Lychee directory and/or Database.

Making that possible would in my opinion be super useful and the only Photo-Management-System in the world capable of doing that.

Ralf.

comment.body:
Hi, I really like the idea and this has been discussed very often, but Lychee needs it's own structure. Changing this would require a lot of adjustments and would not work with existing installations. It's a decision which should have been done different before starting with the project. More here: https://github.com/electerious/Lychee/issues/233

What would be possible: Storing Lychee's structure in a different folder (but I guess that's not what you want)

issue.body:
Currently the package updater creates a folder for each package version in _output. When the _output folder is checked into a Git repository, this is unnecessary and only results in a more bloated repository. Git is already a versioning system, so it would be straightforward to version the package versions in the _output folder with Git.

Therefore an option to do that and to make an automatic commit after each package update would be nice.
